Re-verify item ${ITEM} against the updated client pins.

The item was rechecked recently against the current schema and Glamsterdam
target. The format and version strings are already current. What changed:
every one of the six client submodules has moved to a branch that carries
its actual Glamsterdam work. Some of those moves landed substantial new
EIP-7732 / EIP-8061 / ePBS implementation that the item body has not yet
been re-verified against.

New pins (verify with `git submodule status` and `bash driver/get_versions.sh`):

* `vendor/lighthouse` — `unstable` HEAD `1a6863118` ("Gloas payload cache",
  2026-05-13). Was on `stable` (v8.1.3, March 2026) which lacked
  ~7400 commits of EIP-7732 / Gloas work.
* `vendor/nimbus` — `unstable` HEAD `3802d96291` (2026-05-13). Was on
  `stable` (v26.3.1, March 2026) which lacked ~230 commits.
* `vendor/prysm` — `EIP-8061` HEAD `0f25a41868` ("Add EIP-8061",
  2026-04-28). This branch is `develop + 1 commit` — the EIP-8061
  churn-helper rework on top of a develop that already merged the
  bulk of ePBS / Gloas work (envelope REST APIs, deferred payload
  processing, ExecutionPayloadEnvelopesByRoot, data column queueing
  for Gloas, etc.).
* `vendor/teku` — `glamsterdam-devnet-2` HEAD `70ad00cbaf` ("Align
  devnet-2 reference with merged PR02 stack", 2026-05-12). 55 commits
  ahead of `master`.
* `vendor/grandine` — `glamsterdam-devnet-3` HEAD `15dd0225d4` ("Fix
  for justified and finalized block payload hashes, used in FCU",
  2026-05-11). 79 commits ahead of `develop`.
* `vendor/lodestar` — still `unstable` HEAD (lodestar merges
  Glamsterdam work directly into `unstable`; no separate feature
  branch).

The audit is now branch-symmetric: each client is pinned to the branch
where its actual Glamsterdam implementation lives. Any claim in the item
body that says "client X has not implemented Gloas Y" may now be a false
positive — re-verify each one.

Concretely:

1. For every per-client claim ("X missing", "Y not wired", "Z still
   uses Electra formula", etc.) in the item body, `grep` the relevant
   client tree at the new pin and confirm whether the surface is present
   or still absent. If present, the claim is a false positive — update
   the body to reflect what's there now. Pay particular attention to
   dispatch idioms: a client may not have a function literally named
   `get_activation_churn_limit` but achieve the same Gloas semantics
   via name-polymorphism (lighthouse style — same accessor name, body
   fork-gates internally), subclass override (teku), compile-time
   `when typeof(state).kind` dispatch (nimbus), runtime version
   dispatch through a wrapper (prysm `ActivationChurnLimitForVersion`),
   `state.is_post_gloas()` predicate (grandine), or `fork >=
   ForkSeq.gloas` ternary (lodestar).

2. The only nimbus claims still known to STAND on `unstable` are the
   stale OR-folds at `vendor/nimbus/beacon_chain/spec/beaconstate.nim:
   60-67` (`has_compounding_withdrawal_credential` ORing in `is_builder_
   withdrawal_credential` at `consensusFork >= ConsensusFork.Gloas`)
   and `:1588-1607` (`get_pending_balance_to_withdraw` summing
   `builder_pending_withdrawals` + `builder_pending_payments` into the
   validator accessor at Gloas). If this item depends on either, the
   claim still holds.

3. If every divergent-source claim vacates after re-verification,
   flip `impact` to `none` and remove `splits` + `# main_md_summary`
   from the front matter AND remove the `## Mainnet reachability`
   H2 section from the body (per the schema rules in
   `driver/item_presubmit.sh`).

4. If splits change (e.g. `[prysm, lighthouse, teku, nimbus, grandine]`
   becomes `[prysm, teku, grandine]` because lighthouse + nimbus no
   longer diverge), update the `splits:` line, the `main_md_summary`
   line, and adjust the body N-vs-M counts.

5. If the item is a meta-audit referencing other items' claims (e.g.
   item #28), update the cross-references to match the new findings.

Other notes:

* `last_update:` → today's date.
* The Hypotheses / Findings / Cross-reference table H2 headings already
  exist; refresh content under them rather than rewriting the structure.
* `bash driver/item_presubmit.sh items/${ITEM}` must pass before commit.
* `git commit` when done with a message that calls out which claims
  vacated and which stood. The user already knows the broader context
  (the two re-pin sweeps), so the per-item commit message can be terse.
